\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
A comparison of well and badly behaved minima in parameter estimation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Sean O'Brien
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
This is a meta-analysis of parameter finding techniques.
 The techniques in question are those of PDF (probability density function)
 parameter fitting to data using NLL (negative log likelihood) and single
 value function minimisation techniques.
 These techniques have very broad application in scientific data analysis.
 The behaviour and stability of the minima was tested when the full and
 partial data was used in the parameter fit.
 The findings showed that when only the partial data was used the minima
 derived different parameter results and that the minima from the partial
 data was highly unstable i.e.
 the results depended heavily on the minimisation initial guess.
 Whereas the fit using the full data was stable and gave repeatable results.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The data consisted of 100,000 points, each consisting of a 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 measurement.
 The 3 parameter PDF 
\begin_inset Formula $P(t,\theta;F,\tau_{1},\tau_{2})$
\end_inset

 used to model the data was a linear mixing of 2 PDFs 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1}(t,\theta;\tau_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{2}(t,\theta;\tau_{2})$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{1}(t,\theta;\tau_{1})=\frac{1}{3\pi\tau_{1}}(1+\cos^{2}\theta)e^{-\frac{t}{\tau_{1}}}\:\:\:\:\:\:P_{2}(t,\theta;\tau_{2})=\frac{1}{\pi\tau_{2}}\sin^{2}e^{-\frac{t}{\tau_{2}}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(t,\theta;F,\tau_{1},\tau_{2})=FP_{1}(t,\theta;\tau_{1})+(1-F)P_{2}(t,\theta;\tau_{2})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The paramters estimated were 
\begin_inset Formula $F,\tau_{1},\tau_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This was done by performing a maximum likelyhood fit.
 Which involves minimising the 
\begin_inset Formula $NLL$
\end_inset

 related to the parameters in question.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
NLL(F,\tau_{1},\tau_{2})=-\sum_{i}\log P(t_{i},\theta_{i};F,\tau_{1},\tau_{2})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Where each 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i},\theta_{i}$
\end_inset

 are points in our dataset.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The minuit minimiser was used throughout, packaged for python as iminuit
 
\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

https://iminuit.readthedocs.io/
\end_layout

\end_inset

 All other calculations were performed by my own python code, which is included
 in the appendix of this report.
 The code, data and plots are also available at 
\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

https://github.com/mrseanman/NumRecProject
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Investigation of 
\begin_inset Formula $P(t,\theta)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
10,000 random 
\begin_inset Formula $(t,\theta)$
\end_inset

 data points were generated simulating the 
\begin_inset Formula $P(t,\theta)$
\end_inset

 PDF.
 The parameters used were 
\begin_inset Formula $F=0.5,\tau_{1}=1.0,\tau_{2}=2.0$
\end_inset

 The random generator employed the box method.
 Some relevant plots are given below.
 The ranges were set as 
\begin_inset Formula $t\in[0,10],\;\theta\in[0,2\pi].$
\end_inset

 The finite range of 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 meant that 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{2}$
\end_inset

 had to be normalised differently such that.
 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1}(t,\theta;\tau_{1})=[3\pi\tau_{1}(1-e^{\frac{-10}{\tau_{1}}})]^{-1}\,\,(1+\cos^{2}\theta)e^{-\frac{t}{\tau_{1}}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{2}(t,\theta;\tau_{1})=[\pi\tau_{2}(1-e^{\frac{-10}{\tau_{2}}})]^{-1}\,\,\sin^{2}\theta e^{-\frac{t}{\tau_{2}}}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

